On this act, Mr. Hodgkin, in the first volume of Italy and Her Jnvaders, p. 740, remarks: “Where the liege- men of a constitutional king change a ministry, the subjects of an elected emperor upset a dynasty.'' The discontented army of Britain was led over to Gaul in the year 407 by Constantine, the third tyrannus, of whose deeds a full account by Dr. Freeman will be found in the English Hz'storical Review, 1886, in his article on “Tyrants of Britain, Gaul and Spain,'’ or in the above-named work of Mr. Hodgkin. At no time, therefore, in the year 407, or subsequently, could any detachment of Roman forces be sent over to Britain, because this usurpation of Constantine, with his four years of power over the Prefecture of the Gauls, was the beginning of the final abandonment. ‘⁴ It was not Britain that gave up Rome, but Rome that gave up Britain.’' By A.D. 446, we know from Cildas, there were hardly any of the old Roman families left in the island.

Between 383 and 389, as has been said, no succour by the empire could have been despatched to Britain ; from 388-9 onwards order and authority were being restored in the XVest by Theodosius the Creat, and continued until 406 or 407. This is, therefore, the interval during which the two expeditions men- tioned by Gildas must have taken place, that is, a period of about eighteen years (AD. 389-407).
